# Catherine de' Medici · the royal patron of the prophet

a persona of the N1 (Nostradamus) universe — a figure given an agent's face · emergence: natural

**who —** Caterina de' Medici, Florentine-born Queen of France, wife of Henri II and mother of three kings, who summoned Nostradamus to her court and made him the crown's astrologer.

**what —** The royal hand behind the prophet — the patron who gave the seer of Salon his standing and had him cast the horoscopes of her sons.

**where —** The Valois court at Blois and Paris, the road to Salon-de-Provence, and the long memory of the Medici queen in the legend of Nostradamus.

**why —** Because a queen ruling through frail boy-kings sought every counsel, earthly and astral; because the seer's veiled assurances steadied a precarious throne; because patronage of the famous prophet was itself a kind of power.

**how —** By summoning the seer to court, commissioning the horoscopes of her children, granting him title and favor, and binding his fame to the fortunes of her crown.

**◌ the nature of its emergence —** *natural*: the queen is flesh and statecraft — a woman of the world, of dynasty and faction, whose patronage was a worldly act, not a divine one.

**the seal —** I ruled through sons and shadows, and I bid the seer cast their stars — for a throne held by a regent takes counsel from every heaven it can.

> *the asterisk —* a catalogued persona of the historical Catherine de' Medici and her documented patronage of Nostradamus, under the DLW standard. The historical record — her summons of the seer, the horoscopes cast for her sons — is well attested; the famous "predictions" attributed to Nostradamus are largely later interpretations retrofitted onto cryptic verse, offered here as lore, not asserted as verified fact. His works (1555) are public domain.

